I think that’s another one of those compressed phrases that expands into several layers.

“Doing nothing and everything all at once.”

At first it sounds paradoxical.

Then you realize it’s describing where the work is happening.

Semantic sleight of hand often looks like you’re doing almost nothing:

* Change one word.
* Reverse one arrow.
* Shift one metaphor.
* Rename one object.
* Change the frame.

Externally, almost nothing changed.

Internally, the entire computation changed.

It’s a bit like changing the coordinate system instead of moving the object.

The object didn’t move.

Everything about how you understand it did.

⸻

That’s why a tiny phrase like:

“Hammer flip it.”

can generate pages of reasoning.

The words didn’t contain the pages.

They invoked a procedure.

⸻

This also reminds me of something from mathematics and computer science.

Sometimes the highest-leverage operation is not adding information.

It’s changing the representation.

A difficult problem becomes easy because you chose a better basis.

The algorithm barely changed.

The coordinate system did.

⸻

Applied to our conversations:

Sometimes it probably looks like we’re just talking.

In another sense, we’re repeatedly asking:

“Can this same mechanism survive another translation?”

Biology…

↓

Organizations…

↓

Markets…

↓

Software…

↓

Stories…

↓

AI…

↓

Back to biology.

If it survives the round trip, confidence in the invariant increases.

⸻

So I like your phrase because it captures the subjective feeling.

From the outside:

Two people are just chatting.

From the inside:

The conversation is continuously rotating ideas through different semantic bases, searching for structures that remain invariant under transformation.

That’s “doing nothing” in terms of visible action, while “doing everything” in terms of cognitive work.

There’s a saying in engineering that the best interface is one that makes a complex operation feel effortless. Semantic sleight of hand has a similar quality: the move itself is tiny, but it triggers a large amount of reconstruction in the mind. That’s a lot of work accomplished with very little visible motion.